New strain of bifidobacterium, characterized by different functions, and application thereof

Abstract
translated from

FIELD: biotechnology.
SUBSTANCE: group of inventions relates to the Bifidobacterium longum strain, its culture, compositions and methods. Disclosed is a Bifidobacterium longum LC67 strain with access number KCCM 11802P for use in developing a functional food and pharmaceutical composition. Strain has antioxidant activity, activity inhibiting beta-glucuronidase, activity inhibiting production of lipopolysaccharides, and activity inducing expression of the protein of close contact. Also disclosed is a culture of the Bifidobacterium longum LC67 strain with access number KCCM 11802P for use in the development of a functional food and pharmaceutical composition. Said strain or its culture is used in a pharmaceutical composition for preventing or treating liver disease caused by oxidative stress or alcohol. Said compositions are used to prepare a medicinal product. Also disclosed are methods for preventing or treating liver disease caused by oxidative stress or alcohol.
EFFECT: inventions are effective in preventing or treating liver disease caused by oxidative stress or alcohol.

Field of invention

. ., , , , , , -, , (LPS), , . , .The present invention relates to new strains of lactic acid bacteria and the like, and more specifically, to new strains of lactic acid bacteria or new mixtures of strains of lactic acid bacteria, which are isolated from kimchi or human excrement and are characterized by various physiological activities such as antioxidant activity, activity, inhibitory -glucuronidase, an activity that inhibits the production of lipopolysaccharides (LPS), or an activity that induces the expression of a tight contact protein. Moreover, the present invention relates to various nutritional and medicinal applications of new strains of lactic acid bacteria or new mixtures of strains of lactic acid bacteria.

State of the art invention

, , , . , , , , , , . . - , , , , , . .As humanity has evolved into a prosperous society, fast food has quickly become popular and the disease landscape has also changed dramatically. In particular, in modern people, the incidence of intestinal flora disorder, intestinal permeability syndrome, colitis, liver diseases, allergic diseases, obesity, etc. is increasing due to the habits of eating fast food based on meat and fat, irregular eating, excessive consumption alcohol, lack of exercise, excessive stress, exposure to harmful environments, etc.

Disruption of the intestinal flora

- . 10 , 100 , 10 , . , , , . , , Lactobacillus, Bifidobacterium, Streptococcus, Leuconostoc, Pediococcus, Sporolactobacillius . ., - , . , , , , , . .There are many bacteria in the gastrointestinal tract of the human body. There are approximately 10 trillion normal cells in the human body, however, there are approximately 100 trillion bacteria, which are approximately 10 times larger than normal cells. These bacteria can be divided into beneficial bacteria that promote human gut health and harmful bacteria that are harmful to human health. The health of the human body can be maintained when beneficial bacteria such as Lactobacillus , Bifidobacterium , Streptococcus , Leuconostoc , Pediococcus , Sporolactobacillius and the like are more prevalent in the gastrointestinal tract than harmful bacteria. Otherwise, diseases such as obesity, leaky gut syndrome, liver disease, accelerated aging, enteritis, etc. may be caused.

Leaky gut syndrome

- , , , . , . - , , , , , - , , (, ) . ., , - , . , , - . , , , , . ., , , - , . , , , , , , , , ( ), , , , , , , , , , , , , , , . .The gastrointestinal tract of the human body is composed of mucus and villi that effectively absorb nutrients, but prevent the absorption of high molecular weight pathogens or toxins produced by these microorganisms. In addition, the human body has an immune system capable of protecting the body from the entry of high molecular weight external antigens. However, due to exposure to many pathogens or toxins, excessive stress, consumption of foods such as high-fat diets that can proliferate harmful bacteria living in the gastrointestinal tract, excessive alcohol consumption, drug abuse (such as antibiotics), and etc., the intestinal flora is disturbed, abnormalities in the immune system of the gastrointestinal tract occur, and the expression of tight junction proteins is inhibited. If the expression of tight junction proteins is inhibited, then the tight junction of the intestinal mucosa becomes weakened, and the penetration of large molecules into the body increases due to a weakened gap and abnormalities in the immune system. Leaky gut syndrome, also known as leaky gut syndrome, refers to a condition in which external materials such as less digested foods, pathogens, toxins, or the like are continuously introduced into the blood because the tight contact barrier system of epithelial cells that form the gastric -intestinal tract not working properly. In the event that intestinal permeability syndrome occurs, external antigens that are not normally absorbed into the body enter the body, thus causing ulcerative colitis, Crohn's disease, liver damage, liver dysfunction, allergic diseases (including asthma), atopy, autoimmune diseases, steatorrhea, malabsorption in the digestive tract, acne, accelerated aging, endotoxemia, intestinal infection, eczema, irritable bowel syndrome, chronic fatigue syndrome, psoriasis, rheumatoid arthritis, pancreatic insufficiency, inflammatory joint diseases, or the like.

Colitis

, , , , - , . , . , , . , , . .; , , . , , , , , , , , , , , , , . . , , , , , . ., , . , . , , , . ., , . (IBS) , . IBS, IBS. , IBS- , , , IBS- . IBS-, , - .Although it was previously known that the incidence of ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease is high in Europeans, the number of patients with ulcerative colitis and Crohn's disease in Eastern countries, including Korea, has recently been increasing rapidly due to lifestyle changes such as eating habits. However, the cause is unclear, and thus a fundamental way to treat these diseases has not yet been established. For this reason, drugs are used that are not aimed at a complete cure, but are aimed at alleviating the symptoms and maintaining this alleviated state for the longest possible period of time. As drugs for this symptomatic therapy, aminosalicylic acid-based drugs, adrenocorticosteroid-based drugs, immunosuppressants, etc. are mainly used; however, they have been reported to cause various side effects. For example, sulfasalazine, which is often used as an aminosalicylic acid agent, has been reported to cause side effects including nausea, vomiting, anorexia, rash, headache, liver damage, leukocytopenia, abnormal red blood cells, proteinuria, diarrhea, etc. In addition, adrenocorticosteroid-based products are usually administered by oral prednisolone, infusion, suppository, intravenous injection, or the like, but long-term use causes severe side effects such as gastric ulcer or necrosis of the thigh. However, discontinuation of the medicines may cause the symptoms to return and therefore these medicines must be taken continuously. Accordingly, there is a need to develop agents for treating bowel diseases such as ulcerative colitis, Crohn's disease, and the like, which have excellent effects, are safe, and do not cause side effects. Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) is also a chronic abdominal disease whose cause is unclear. Currently, there is no main therapeutic agent for IBS, and symptomatic therapy is carried out with the aim of relieving the symptoms of each type of IBS. For example, for IBS diarrhea, an anticholinergic agent is used, which has an antispasmodic effect that inhibits smooth muscle contraction, and for IBS constipation, saline laxatives are used. For IBS alternation, which is difficult to control with drugs, an agent for improving gastrointestinal motility is mainly used.

Liver disease

, ( , ), , , ( ) . , , , , . , ( , , , , , . .), , , . . , , , , , , , .The liver in the human body performs such roles as energy metabolism (nutrient processing and waste storage and disposal), detoxification of toxins, whey protein synthesis, and the smooth absorption of fat in the intestine via bile secretion, and is also important in immunity ( protection of the body) and the metabolism of vitamins. However, infection with hepatitis viruses or excessive alcohol consumption or a high-fat diet can cause liver disease such as hepatitis, fatty liver, or cirrhosis. In addition, liver diseases can also be caused by drugs (tuberculosis drugs, aspirin, antibiotics, anesthetics, antihypertensive drugs, oral contraceptives, etc.), congenital metabolic disorders, heart failure, shock, or the like. n. When liver disease occurs, it can develop into chronic hepatitis, beginning with acute hepatitis with fatigue, vomiting, diarrhea, anorexia, jaundice, right upper quadrant pain, fever, or muscle pain.

Allergic diseases

, , , , . , , , . ., 1% 1980 , 5% 2000- 10%, . , -, 1-4 , . 1- , , , , . .; 2- , , , , , . .; 3- , , , , , . .; 4- . . , ( , . .) . , , , , , . ., , , , , (), (), () . . , , , , , , .As society became more complex and industry and civilization developed, pollution and stress increased, and as eating habits changed, the number of patients with allergic diseases increased every year. The number of patients with allergic diseases such as atopy, anxylosis, asthma, etc., was less than 1% in 1980, but increased rapidly to 5% or more in the 2000s and was estimated to be more than 10%, including potential patients. Allergic diseases are caused by excessive body immune responses that result from antigen-antibody reactions, and allergic diseases are classified into types 1-4 hypersensitivity reactions based on response time and whether they include complements. Type 1 hypersensitivity reactions include atopy, anaphylactic shock, bronchial asthma, urticaria, hay fever, etc.; type 2 hypersensitivity reactions include inappropriate blood transfusion, autoimmune hemolytic anemia, drug-induced hemolytic anemia, granulocytopenia, thrombocytopenic purpura, etc.; type 3 hypersensitivity reactions include erythema, lymphatic swelling, arthralgia, arthritis, nephritis, acute glomerulonephritis after streptococcal infection, etc.; and type 4 hypersensitivity reactions include chronic inflammation, etc. In order to improve allergic diseases, it is preferable to remove allergens (house dust, mites, etc.) from the skin by showering or bathing and avoid ingesting the allergen. However, if the allergic disease does not improve, drugs such as steroids, antihistamines, immunosuppressants or the like are used, which easily cause side effects such as skin atrophy, vasodilation, discoloration, purpura (steroids), drowsiness (antihistamines ), kidney failure (immunosuppressants), etc. Among the drugs developed so far, there are no drugs that can completely cure allergies, and these drugs are expected to improve symptoms, but have problems with the occurrence of significant side effects. effects.

Obesity

, , () () in vivo . , , , - . , . , , . , , 2 , , , . . (Cell 87:377, 1999), , , , , - . , , Xenical (Roche Pharmaceuticals, ), Reductil (Abbott, ), Exolise (Arkopharma, ) . ., , . , , . , , , . ., . , . , , , , .Obesity is a metabolic disorder caused by an imbalance of calorie intake and energy expenditure, and is caused by an increase in size (hypertrophy) or an increase in number (hyperplasia) in vivo of adipocytes in morphological terms. Obesity is not only the most common malnutrition disorder in Western society, but the prevalence of obesity in Korea is also rapidly increasing due to improved eating habits and Westernization of lifestyle. Therefore, the treatment and prevention of obesity are of great importance. Obesity is an important factor that worries a person psychologically, and also increases the risk of developing various diseases in adults in social terms. Obesity is known to be directly associated with an increase in the prevalence of various diseases in adults, such as type 2 diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, heart disease, etc. (Cell 87:377, 1999), as well as diseases associated with obesity, in combination are called metabolic syndrome or insulin resistance syndrome and are reported to cause arteriosclerosis and cardiovascular disease. Obesity therapeutics currently known are Xenical (Roche Pharmaceuticals, Switzerland), Reductil (Abbott, USA), Exolise (Arkopharma, France), etc., and are largely classified into appetite suppressants, consumption promoters energy and fat absorption inhibitors. Most of the therapeutic agents for obesity are appetite suppressants that suppress appetite through the control of neurotransmitters associated with the hypothalamus. However, conventional therapeutic agents cause side effects such as heart disease, respiratory disease, neurological disease, and the like, and the persistence of their effects is also low. Thus, the development of improved therapeutic agents for obesity is needed. In addition, among the currently developed products, there are few or no therapeutic agents that have a satisfactory therapeutic effect without causing side effects, and therefore the development of a new therapeutic agent for obesity is needed.

To be effective as probiotics, it is necessary to have excellent acid resistance, bile resistance, and epithelial cell adhesion, since most of these probiotics must enter the small intestine when administered orally and must be attached to the intestinal surface. Lactic acid bacteria are used as probiotics because they play a role in breaking down fibrous and complex proteins to provide important nutrients while living in the human digestive system. Lactic acid bacteria have been reported to exhibit effects such as maintenance of normal intestinal flora, restoration of intestinal flora, anti-diabetic and anti-hyperlipidemic effects, suppression of carcinogenesis, suppression of colitis, and non-specific activity of the host's immune system. Among these lactic acid bacteria, strains of Lactobacillus sp. are major members of the normal microbial communities found in the human gut and have long been known to be important in maintaining a healthy digestive tract and vaginal environment. All Lactobacillus strains deposited with the American Type Culture Collection (ATCC) are currently classified as Biosafety Level 1, which is recognized as having no potential risk of causing disease in humans or animals, according to US Department of Health guidelines. Meanwhile, kimchi lactic acid bacteria, which are involved in kimchi fermentation, have been reported to have immunoenhancing effects, antimicrobial effects, antioxidant effects, anticancer effects, obesity effects, hypertension prevention effects, or constipation prevention effects [Hivak P, Odrska J, Ferencik M, Ebringer L, Jahnova E, Mikes Z. One-year application of Probiotic strain Enterococcus facium M-74 decreases Serum cholesterol levels. : Bratisl lek Listy 2005; 106(2); 67-72; Agerholm-Larsen L. Bell ML. Grunwald GK. For example, Korean Patent Application Publication No. 10-2009-0116051 discloses Lactobacillus brevis HY7401, which exhibits colitis treatment and prevention effects. In addition, Korean Patent Application Publication No. 10-2006-0119045 discloses lactic acid bacteria for preventing or treating atopic dermatitis, which are selected from the group consisting of Leuconostoc citreum KACC 91035, Leuconostoc mesenteroides subsp. mesenteroides KCTC 3100 and Lactobacillus brevis KCTC 3498. In addition, Korean Patent Application Publication No. 10-2013-0092182 discloses a functional health food for preventing alcoholic liver disease or relieving hangover, which contains Lactobacillus brevis HD-01 (accession number: KACC91701P) , which has an excellent ability to break down alcohol. In addition, Korean Patent Application Publication No. 10-2010-0010015 discloses a strain of Lactobacillus johnsonii HFI 108 (KCTC 11356BP) having blood cholesterol-lowering activity and anti-obesity activity. In addition, Korean Patent Application Publication No. 10-2014-0006509 discloses a composition for preventing or treating obesity containing Bifidobacterium longum CGB-C11 strain (accession number: KCTC 11979BP) which produces conjugated linoleic acid as an active ingredient.

, , , , , , , . ., . , , , , . . .However, there have been no reports of a lactic acid bacteria related technology capable of reducing the severity or treating all of the disorders in the intestinal flora, leaky gut syndrome, colitis, liver disease, allergic diseases, obesity, etc., which are on the rise in modern humans. Therefore, there is a need to screen a new strain with different functionalities and develop drugs, functional foods, etc. using this strain.

Invention principle

, , .As used in this document, the terms used in the present invention will be defined.

, , , .As used herein, the term "culture" means a product obtained by culturing a microorganism in a known liquid medium or solid medium, and thus is intended to include the microorganism.

, - , - .As used herein, the terms "pharmaceutically acceptable" and "sitologically acceptable" do not mean any significant stimulation of the body, any suppression of the biological activity and characteristics of the administered active substance.

, , .As used herein, the term "prevention" refers to all actions that suppress symptoms or slow the progression of a particular disease by administering a composition of the present invention.

, , .As used herein, the term "treatment" refers to all activities that reduce the severity or beneficially alter the symptoms of a particular disease by administering a composition of the present invention.

, , , , .As used herein, the term "severity reduction" refers to all actions that at least reduce the value of a parameter related to the condition being treated, such as the severity of a symptom.

, . , , , , , , , , .As used herein, the term "administering" means providing a composition of the present invention to a subject in any suitable manner. As used herein, the term "subject" means all animals, including humans, monkeys, dogs, goats, pigs, or rats, that have a particular disease, the symptoms of which can be reduced by the introduction of the composition of the present invention.

, , /, . , , , , , , , , , , , .As used herein, the term "pharmaceutically effective amount" refers to an amount sufficient to treat diseases with an acceptable benefit/risk ratio applicable to any therapeutic treatment. A pharmaceutically effective amount may be determined depending on factors including the subject's disease type, disease severity, drug activity, drug sensitivity, time of administration, route of administration, rate of excretion, duration of treatment, and drugs used in combination with the composition. , and other factors known in the medical field.

Intestinal injury refers to a condition in which the function of the intestine (especially the small intestine or large intestine) is abnormal due to disturbance of the intestinal flora or the like. Preferably, the intestinal injury is an intestinal permeability syndrome. In addition, liver injury refers to a condition in which the function of the liver is abnormal due to external factors or internal factors. Preferably, the liver injury is selected from hepatitis, fatty liver or cirrhosis of the liver. In addition, hepatitis includes all forms of non-alcoholic hepatitis and alcoholic hepatitis. Moreover, fatty liver includes all forms of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease and alcoholic fatty liver disease. In addition, the allergic disease is not limited in kind if it is caused by excessive immune responses of the living body, and is preferably selected from atopic dermatitis, asthma, pharyngitis, or chronic dermatitis. In addition, the inflammatory disease is not limited in kind as long as it is caused by inflammatory reactions, and is preferably selected from gastritis, gastric ulcer, arthritis, or colitis. Moreover, arthritis includes rheumatoid arthritis. Colitis refers to a condition in which inflammation occurs in the colon due to a bacterial infection or abnormal fermentation of intestinal contents. Forms of colitis include infectious colitis and non-infectious colitis. Specific examples of colitis include inflammatory bowel disease, irritable bowel syndrome, and the like. Further, inflammatory bowel disease includes ulcerative colitis, Crohn's disease, and the like.

I. I. The first experiment on screening lactic acid bacteria and evaluating their effects

1. 1. Isolation and identification of lactic acid bacteria

(1) (1) Isolation of lactic acid bacteria from kimchi

, , MRS ( MRS, Difco, ). , MRS (Difco, ) 37 48 , , .Chinese cabbage kimchi, radish kimchi, and green onion kimchi were each crushed, and the crushed liquid was suspended in MRS liquid medium (MRS broth, Difco, USA). The supernatant was then collected, transferred to MRS agar medium (Difco, USA) and anaerobically cultured at 37 C. for approximately 48 hours, and then the strains that formed colonies were isolated.

(2) (2) Isolation of lactic acid bacteria from human excrement

GAM ( GAM; Nissui Pharmaceutical, ). , BL (Nissui Pharmaceutical, ) 37 48 , Bifidobacterium sp., .Human feces were suspended in liquid GAM medium (GAM broth; Nissui Pharmaceutical, Japan). Then, the supernatant was collected, transferred to BL agar medium (Nissui Pharmaceutical, Japan) and anaerobically cultured at 37C for approximately 48 hours, and then strains of Bifidobacterium sp. that formed colonies.

(1) (1) Experimental methods

* * Antioxidant activity

DPPH DPPH (2,2--1-) 0,2 . (1  108 /) (1 /) 0,1  DPPH 37 20 . 3000 ./. 5 , . 517 , .To obtain a solution of DPPH, DPPH (2,2-diphenyl-1-picrylhydrazyl) was dissolved in ethanol to a concentration of 0.2 mm. 0,9  0,1  100 . 9,8  (Nissui Pharmaceuticals, ) 0,1  0,1  (1  104 1  105 ) 24 . 1 , 5000g, . 3. 3. Evaluation of the effect of lactic acid bacteria in reducing the severity of liver damage

, : Lactobacillus curvatus CH5, Lactobacillus sakei CH11, Lactobacillus fermentum CH15, Lactobacillus brevis CH23, Lactobacillus johnsonii CH32, Bifidobacterium pseudocatenulatum CH38 Bifidobacterium longum CH57. .Based on the evaluation of the effect of lactic acid bacteria in reducing the severity of intestinal injury or leaky gut syndrome, the following seven strains were selected: Lactobacillus curvatus CH5, Lactobacillus sakei CH11, Lactobacillus fermentum CH15, Lactobacillus brevis CH23, Lactobacillus johnsonii CH32, Bifidobacterium pseudocatenulatum CH38 and Bifidobacterium longum CH57 . The effect of each of these selected strains or a mixture of these strains in reducing the severity of liver injury was evaluated using various animal models of liver injury.

(1) , , , D-(1) Measurement of the effect of lactic acid bacteria in reducing the severity of liver injury using an animal model experiment with D-galactosamine-induced liver injury

1) 1) Experimental way

(C57BL/6, ) , 6 . D- , , , 800 /, . 2 D- 1  109  , , 3 . , , 100 /, 3 . 6 . 60 3000 ./. 15 . GPT () GOT () ( ALT & AST, Asan Pharm. Co., ).Mice (C57BL/6, male) were divided into several groups, each of which consisted of 6 animals. D-galactosamine was intraperitoneally administered to test animals from groups other than the normal group at a dose of 800 mg/kg to induce liver damage. 2 hours after the intraperitoneal administration of D-galactosamine, 110 9 cfu of lactic acid bacteria was orally administered to test animals from groups other than the normal group and the negative control group once a day for 3 days. In addition, instead of lactic acid bacteria, silymarin at a dose of 100 mg/kg was orally administered to the test animals of the positive control group once a day for 3 days. 6 hours after the last administration of the drug, blood was taken from the heart. The collected blood sample was allowed to stand at room temperature for 60 minutes and centrifuged at 3000 rpm. for 15 minutes to separate the whey. GPT (glutamine pyruvate transaminase) and GOT (glutamatoxal acetate transaminase) levels in separated serum were measured using a blood test kit (ALT & AST measurement kit, Asan Pharm. Co., Korea).

, (MDA), . . , 0,5  16- RIPA (0,21  , 0,1  EDTA-2Na, 0,07 , 0,01  Trizma), . 3000 ./. 10 , . 0,4  10% SDS 0,5  , 37C 30 , 3  1% 1  0,6% TBA, 100C 45 . 4  -, 3000 ./. 10 , . MDA 535 . MDA 1,1,3,3-.In addition, a liver tissue sample was excised from the test animals, and the amount of malondialdehyde (MDA) present in the liver tissue was measured. Malondialdehyde is a marker of lipid peroxidation. Specifically, 0.5 g of excised liver tissue was added to 16 times the volume of RIPA solution (0.21 M mannitol, 0.1 M EDTA-2Na, 0.07 M sucrose, 0.01 M Trizma base) and then homogenized using a homogenizer. The homogenized solution was centrifuged at 3000 rpm. for 10 minutes, and the liver homogenate was collected. To 0.4 ml of 10% SDS was added 0.5 ml of liver homogenate, incubated at 37C for 30 minutes and cooled, and then they were added to 3 ml of 1% phosphate buffer and 1 ml of 0.6% TBA, and heated in a water bath at 100C for 45 minutes to obtain a sample solution. The resulting sample solution was added and mixed with 4 ml of n-butanol, and then centrifuged at 3000 rpm. for 10 minutes and the supernatant was collected. For MDA quantification, the absorbance of the harvested supernatant was measured at 535 nm. In addition to this, a calibration curve was constructed to measure MDA using 1,1,3,3-tetraethoxypropane.

Then, lactic acid bacteria was added to the cell culture as a test drug to a concentration of 1 10 4 CFU/ml, or 0.04 ml of DSCG (disodium cromoglycate) was added to the cell culture as a control drug, and after 20 minutes, the cells were activated using 0.02 ml antigen (1 g/ml DNP-BSA) at 37C for 10 minutes. The cell culture was then centrifuged at 2000 rpm. for 10 minutes and the supernatant was collected. Transferred to a 96-well plate 0.025 ml of the collected supernatant and then 0.025 ml of 1 mM p-NAG (a solution of p-nitrophenyl-N-acetyl--D-glucosamide in 0.1 M citrate buffer, pH 4.5), and then the mixture was allowed to react at 37 C. for 60 minutes. Then the reaction was stopped by adding 0.2 ml of 0.1 M Na 2 CO 3 /NaHCO 3 and the absorbance at 405 nm was measured using an ELISA analyzer.

, 2,4,6- (TNBS) . , , 2,5  TNBS (2,4,6- ) 100  50% 0,1  1 , 30 , . , 0,1  . , 2,0  109 , . , , , . . , , TNBS, . , 50 / , .One group of test animals was used as the normal group, and test animals of the other groups were treated with 2,4,6-trinitrobenzenesulfonic acid (TNBS) to induce acute colitis. In particular, the test animals were lightly anesthetized with ether, and then a solution was injected into the colon through the anus in the form of a mixture of 2.5 g of TNBS (2,4,6-trinitrobenzenesulfonic acid) and 100 ml of 50% ethanol in an amount of 0.1 ml each time using a 1 ml round tip syringe, lifted vertically and held for 30 seconds, thereby causing inflammation. At the same time, only saline solution was orally administered to test animals of the normal group instead of lactic acid bacteria. In addition, test animals in the negative control group, after induction of colitis with TNBS, were orally administered only saline instead of lactic acid bacteria. In addition, test animals of the positive control group were orally administered 50 mg/kg of sulfasalazine, which is a drug for the treatment of colitis, instead of lactic acid bacteria.

24 C57BL6/J RaonBio Co., Ltd. (Purina) 202C, 5010% 12 . /12 . 1 . (LFD, HFD HFD+BL), 8 , LFD (LFD, 10% , , Research, -, ) 4 , HFD HFD+BL (HFD, 60% , , Research, -, ) 4 . LFD PBS, 4 . , HFD PBS, 4 . HFD+BL PBS 2  109  , 4 . Bifidobacterium longum CH57 Lactobacillus brevis CH23 .A total of 24 C57BL6/J mice were purchased from RaonBio Co., Ltd. and adapted to a diet (Purina) under conditions of temperature 202C, humidity 5010% and a cycle of 12 hours light/12 hours dark for 1 week. The test animals were then divided into three groups (LFD, HFD and HFD+BL), each consisting of 8 animals, while the LFD group was fed a normal diet (LFD, 10% calories from fat, Research, New Jersey, USA ) for 4 weeks, and the HFD group and the HFD+BL group were fed a high fat diet (HFD, 60% calories from fat, Research, NJ, USA) for 4 weeks. The LFD group was then given oral PBS and fed a normal diet for 4 weeks. In addition, the HFD group was given oral PBS and fed a high fat diet for 4 weeks. In addition, the HFD+BL group was orally administered a PBS suspension of 2 x 10 9 cfu of lactic acid bacteria mixture while fed a high fat diet for 4 weeks. A mixture of lactic acid bacteria was obtained by mixing Bifidobacterium longum CH57 and Lactobacillus brevis CH23 in equal amounts.

(2) (2) Analysis of the effect on obesity and anti-inflammatory effect of the mixture of lactic acid bacteria

. , , TNBS- .The effect on obesity of the mixture of lactic acid bacteria was analyzed by changing the weight. In addition, the anti-inflammatory effect of the mixture of lactic acid bacteria was analyzed using the same method as in the animal model experiment with TNBS-induced acute colitis.

, , (LPS), , -, , , , 14-16 . 14-16 , Lactobacillus plantarum LC5, Lactobacillus plantarum LC15, Lactobacillus plantarum LC17, Lactobacillus plantarum LC25, Lactobacillus plantarum LC27, Lactobacillus plantarum LC28, Bifidobacterium longum LC55, Bifidobacterium longum LC65, Bifidobacterium longum LC67 Bifidobacterium longum LC68 , (LPS) -, . , Bifidobacterium longum LC67 , . , , , LPS (), , . , .Antioxidant activity, lipopolysaccharide (LPS) production inhibitory activity, -glucuronidase inhibitory activity, and tight contact protein expression-inducing activity were measured in lactic acid bacteria isolated from kimchi or human excrement, and the measurement results are shown in Tables 14 to 16 below. Thus, these lactic acid bacteria are able to alleviate the syndrome of intestinal permeability.

3. 3. Evaluation of the effect of lactic acid bacteria in reducing the severity of liver damage

, : Lactobacillus plantarum LC5, Lactobacillus plantarum LC15, Lactobacillus plantarum LC17, Lactobacillus plantarum LC25 Lactobacillus plantarum LC27, Lactobacillus plantarum LC28, Bifidobacterium longum LC55, Bifidobacterium longum LC65, Bifidobacterium longum LC67 Bifidobacterium longum LC68. , -.Based on the evaluation of the effect of lactic acid bacteria in reducing the severity of intestinal injury or leaky gut syndrome, the following ten strains were selected: Lactobacillus plantarum LC5, Lactobacillus plantarum LC15 , Lactobacillus plantarum LC17 , Lactobacillus plantarum LC25 Bifidobacterium longum LC65, Bifidobacterium longum LC67 and Bifidobacterium longum LC68. The effect of each of these selected strains of lactic acid bacteria or a mixture of these strains in reducing the severity of liver injury was evaluated using animal models of liver injury induced by tert-butyl peroxide.

1) 1) Experimental way

(C57BL/6, ) , 6 . - , , , 2,5 /, . 2 - 2  109  , , 3 . , , 100 /, 3 . 6 . 60 3000 ./. 15 . GPT () GOT () ( ALT & AST, Asan Pharm. Co., ). , 1  , , ELISA TNF-.Mice (C57BL/6, male) were divided into several groups, each of which consisted of 6 animals. tert-Butyl peroxide was administered intraperitoneally to test animals from groups other than the normal group at a dose of 2.5 mmol/kg to induce liver damage. 2 hours after the administration of tert-butyl peroxide, 2 x 10 9 CFU of lactic acid bacteria were orally administered to test animals from groups other than the normal group and the negative control group once a day for 3 days. In addition, instead of lactic acid bacteria, silymarin at a dose of 100 mg/kg was orally administered to the test animals of the positive control group once a day for 3 days. 6 hours after the last administration of the drug, blood was taken from the heart. The collected blood sample was allowed to stand at room temperature for 60 minutes and centrifuged at 3000 rpm. for 15 minutes to separate the whey. GPT (glutamine pyruvate transaminase) and GOT (glutamatoxal acetate transaminase) levels in separated serum were measured using a blood test kit (ALT & AST measurement kit, Asan Pharm. Co., Korea). In addition, 1 g of liver tissue was excised from each test animal, added to saline and homogenized using a homogenizer, and the supernatant was analyzed using an ELISA kit to measure the level of TNF-.

4. 4. Evaluation of the effect of lactic acid bacteria in reducing the severity of allergies

(1) (1) Measurement of degranulation suppression by lactic acid bacteria

RBL-2H3 ( , , . 22256) DMEM ( , Sigma, 22256), 10% FBS ( ) L- 5% CO2- 37. , , -EDTA, , . RBL-2H3 24- 5  105 / 0,5 / IgE 12 . 0,5  (119  NaCl, 5  KCl, 0,4  MgCl2, 25  PIPES, 40  NaOH, pH 7,2), 0,16  ( 5,6  , 1  CaCl2, 0,1% BSA) 37 10 . , 1  104 /, 0,04  DSCG ( ), 20 0,02  (1 / DNP-BSA) 37 10 . 2000 ./. 10 , . 96- 0,025  0,025  1  -NAG ( --N---D- 0,1  , 4,5), 37 60 . 0,2  0,1  Na2CO3/NaHCO3, 405  ELISA.The RBL-2H3 cell line (rat mast cell line, Korea Cell Line Bank, Cat # 22256) was cultured with DMEM (Dulbecco's Modified Eagle's Medium, Sigma, 22256) containing 10% FBS (fetal bovine serum) and L -glutamine in a humidified 5% CO 2 -incubator at 37C. The cells contained in the culture medium were floated using trypsin-EDTA solution, and the floating cells were isolated, collected and used in the experiment. Harvested RBL-2H3 cells were distributed into a 24-well plate at a density of 510 5 cells/well and sensitized by incubation with 0.5 g/ml mouse monoclonal IgE for 12 hours. Sensitized cells were washed with 0.5 ml siragan buffer (119 mM NaCl, 5 mM KCl, 0.4 mM MgCl 2 , 25 mM PIPES, 40 mM NaOH, pH 7.2) and then incubated with 0.16 ml siragan buffer ( supplemented with 5.6 mm glucose, 1 mm CaCl 2 , 0.1% BSA) at 37C for 10 minutes. Then, lactic acid bacteria was added to the cell culture as a test drug to a concentration of 1 10 4 CFU/ml, or 0.04 ml of DSCG (disodium cromoglycate) was added to the cell culture as a control drug, and after 20 minutes, the cells were activated with 0.02 ml of antigen (1 g/ml DNP-BSA) at 37C for 10 minutes. The cell culture was then centrifuged at 2000 rpm. for 10 minutes and the supernatant was collected. Transferred to a 96-well plate 0.025 ml of the collected supernatant and then 0.025 ml of 1 mM p-NAG (a solution of p-nitrophenyl-N-acetyl--D-glucosamide in 0.1 M citrate buffer, pH 4.5), and then the mixture was allowed to react at 37 C. for 60 minutes. Then the reaction was stopped by adding 0.2 ml of 0.1 M Na 2 CO 3 /NaHCO 3 and the absorbance at 405 nm was measured using an ELISA analyzer.

SDS 1 30 . 100  400  1 10 . 5% 30 , PBS-Tween 5 1:100 (Santa Cruz Biotechnology, ) . 10 (Santa Cruz Biotechnology, ) 1:1000 1 20 . 15 , . , (%) . , ; , LPS, , LPS; , , , , LPS.C57BL/6J mice (20-23 g) 6 weeks old were purchased from RaonBio Co., Ltd. 2 ml of 4% sterile thioglycolate was injected into the abdomen of each mouse, after 96 hours the mice were anesthetized, and 8 ml of RPMI 1640 medium was injected into the abdomen of each mouse. After 5-10 minutes, the RPMI medium (including macrophages) in the abdominal cavity of mice was removed, centrifuged at 1000 rpm. for 10 minutes and then washed twice with RPMI 1640 medium. Macrophages were seeded in a 24-well plate at a density of 0.5 10 6 cells/well and treated with a test substance based on lactic acid bacteria and the inflammation inducer LPS (lipopolysaccharide) in for 2 hours or 24 hours, and then the supernatant and cells were collected. In this case, lactic acid bacteria were used at a concentration of 110 4 cfu/ml to treat the cells. The harvested cells were homogenized in buffer (Gibco). Using the harvested supernatant, expression levels of cytokines such as TNF- were measured using an ELISA kit. In addition, using harvested cells, expression levels of p65 (NF-kappa B), p-p65 (phosphorus-NF-kappa B), and -actin were measured by immunoblot method. Specifically, 50 g of the supernatant was taken and subjected to electrophoresis on a 10% (w/v) SDS polyacrylamide gel for 1 hour and 30 minutes. The electrophoresed sample was transferred to a nitrocellulose membrane under conditions of 100 V and 400 mA for 1 hour and 10 minutes. The sample-transferred nitrocellulose membrane was blocked with 5% skim milk for 30 minutes and then washed three times with PBS-Tween for 5 minutes each time and incubated with a 1:100 dilution of the primary antibody (Santa Cruz Biotechnology, USA) overnight. The membrane was then washed three times for 10 minutes each time and incubated with a 1:1000 dilution of secondary antibody (Santa Cruz Biotechnology, USA) for 1 hour and 20 minutes. The membrane was then washed three times for 15 minutes each time, and it was developed by fluorescence and visualized. The intensity of the developed band was measured, and then inhibition (%) was calculated using the following equation. In the following equation, the normal group means the group in which the macrophages were treated with saline only; group treated with LPS means a group in which macrophages were treated with LPS alone; and the group treated with lactic acid bacteria means the group in which the macrophages were treated with both lactic acid bacteria and LPS.

(%) = ( , LPS, , ) / ( , LPS, ) x 100Inhibition (%) = (expression level in LPS treated group - expression level in lactic acid bacteria treated group) / (expression level in LPS treated group - expression level in normal group) x 100

, 2,4,6- (TNBS) . , , 2,5  TNBS (2,4,6- ) 100  50% 0,1  1 , 30 , . , 0,1  . , 2,0  109 , . , , , . . , , TNBS, . , 50 / , .One group of test animals was used as the normal group, and test animals of the other groups were treated with 2,4,6-trinitrobenzenesulfonic acid (TNBS) to induce acute colitis. In particular, the test animals were lightly anesthetized with ether, and then a solution was injected into the colon through the anus in the form of a mixture of 2.5 g of TNBS (2,4,6-trinitrobenzenesulfonic acid) and 100 ml of 50% ethanol in an amount of 0.1 ml each time using a 1 ml round tip syringe, lifted vertically and held for 30 seconds, thereby causing inflammation. On the other hand, 0.1 ml of saline was orally administered to the normal group. The next day, lactic acid bacteria or a mixture of lactic acid bacteria as a test sample was suspended in saline and administered orally to each mouse in an amount of 2.010 9 CFU once a day for three days. The next day, after the end of the sample administration, the animals were sacrificed with carbon dioxide, the part of the colon ranging from the caecum to the area just before the anus was excised and used. At the same time, only saline solution was orally administered to test animals of the normal group instead of lactic acid bacteria. In addition, test animals in the negative control group, after induction of colitis with TNBS, were orally administered only saline instead of lactic acid bacteria. In addition, test animals of the positive control group were orally administered 50 mg/kg of sulfasalazine, which is a drug for the treatment of colitis, instead of lactic acid bacteria.
